<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CYLINDER
        SLEEVES - Inspection
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="7">
        <title>Inspection</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect inside surface of sleeve for scuffing or scoring and polishing. Replace
                sleeve (and piston) as required. Examine outer surface of sleeve for cavitation erosion, replace as
                required.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check cylinder sleeves for wear (taper) using any one of the three methods described.</para>
        </step1>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Method One</title>
            <para>"
                <emph type="bold">TELESCOPING GAUGE METHOD</emph>" (Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050620">6.20</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                and
                <emph type="bold">
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050621">6.21</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
            <para>Using a telescoping gauge, and an outside micrometer:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure sleeve I.D. at top of piston ring travel (just below carbon ridge area) (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure 6.21</emph>) and record reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure sleeve. I.D. below ring travel area (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050622">6.22</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ) and record reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The difference between two readings is cylinder sleeve taper. If specifications are
                    exceeded, replace sleeve.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050619" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2425" filename="../figeg2/EG2425.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.19.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Piston Pin</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Connecting Rod</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050620" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11866" filename="../figcg1/CG11866.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.20.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050621" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2421" filename="../figeg2/EG2421.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.21.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Micrometer</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Telescoping Gauge</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Cylinder Sleeve</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Method Two</title>
            <para>"
                <emph type="bold">DIAL BORE GAUGE METHOD</emph>" (Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050622">6.22</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050623">6.23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <para>Using a dial bore gauge:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure at the top of the piston ring travel just below the carbon ridge area) (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050622">6.22</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ) and record the reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure below ring travel area (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050623">6.23</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ) and record the reading.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para>The difference between the two readings is the cylinder sleeve taper. If specifications are exceeded,
                replace sleeve.
            </para>
            <figure id="ef1050622" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg12111" filename="../figcg1/CG12111.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.22.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1050623" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg2422" filename="../figeg2/EG2422.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.23.</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Dial Bore Gauge</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Sleeve</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Method Three</title>
            <para>"
                <emph type="bold">FEELER GAUGE METHOD</emph>" (Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figures
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050624">6.24</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                and
                <emph type="bold">
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050625">6.25</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                )
                <emph type="bold">.</emph>
            </para>
            <para>Install a top compression ring squarely at top of ring travel (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050624">6.24</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ) and measure ring end gap with a feeler gauge. Record reading.
            </para>
            <para>Install same piston ring squarely below ring travel area (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050625">6.25</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ) and measure ring end gap. Record readings.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use a piston to be sure ring is seated squarely into bore.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>Every 0.003 in. (0.07 mm) increase in ring gap equals a 0.001 in. (0.025 mm) increase in bore size.
            </para>
            <para>If sleeve is worn beyond specifications, replace sleeve.</para>
            <figure id="ef1050624" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11864" filename="../figcg1/CG11864.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.24.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1050625" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg12114" filename="../figcg1/CG12114.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.25.</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
